snippet.textDisplay:
I was on drugs for a while and finally went to rehab and got clean. I wrote this poem while I was in rehab in the Tuscaloosa, Al. VA. but the poem is mostly about my ptsd from being in Iraq while I was serving my 4 years active duty in the marine corps. I would really like to see what you could do with it and it would mean a lot to me. Thanks.


Tab Waddell



The Demons I Wield:


I'm stuck in a well of never ending darkness,

No lights and no exit, Just cries and pure silence, thats louder than all noises,

Panic and Anxiety with just sadness and scars,

I went to boot camp for training, and then straight to war.

Life as I knew it, would be the same nevermore,

I was taught to fight and brainwashed to kill,

All of my friends and enemies in blood pools lie still

Awaken in my sleep, I'm screaming with chills,

Forever they'll remain, like the scars burnt in my brain,

By sights and smells, they haunt me now,

But the scars never seen, are the demons I wield,

So many things I bottle up, and lock inside,

Sometimes I'm angry, and sometimes i cry but the demons I wield I keep locked deep down inside,

All the things that I've seen, most everything I have done, are the heavier things I wouldn't wish upon anyone,

My friends and foes, have dropped like cases, like the bullets being fired through innocent faces,

The war goes on, they say that I'm done, and send me back home, but MY WAR had really just begun,

Sleeping and seeing all the people, places and faces, make my mind drift into very dark spaces,

Survivors remorse has led me astray, living this life I could never stay here this way,

In my 1911 chamber i did say, lord I'm in hell, please take my demons away,

The hammer I heard fall, but the round i did not, God was telling me he had forgotten me not.

Even if to no one, else in the world, to him my guilted life, was worth forever more,

This is just the tip of my supersized iceberg,

My ship I will not sink, and my shepherd won't lose his herd,

I know now forever My demons can't, be completely cured, 

Like my shepherd I will always, keep tending my herd.

snippet.textDisplay:
Im surprised no one has made this observation but..

Tom MacDonald is an artist who is about the message (getting the truth to as many people/KIDS as possible) and not about being famous or the money. So every time he comes out with a song that is popular and gets more and more famous, unfortunately he's going to feel this way ("I am everything I hate"). He's gonna feel like he's not being true to himself and his depression and anxiety is gonna feed off of that and make him feel 10xs worse.


Tom, don't feel guilty for becoming more famous. This just means you are reaching more kids and get to reach that many more. You're saving lives with your music. Remember that you ARE being true to yourself because your speaking the truth and YOUR TRUTH in your songs. Keep you're head up and keep the music coming. I learn something new that opens my eyes and I can't wait to learn more.

Im sure I speak for many of your fans when I say that.

Much love from a fan.

There are like maybe 3 or 4 songs that can genuinely make me tear up. Tom, you have made that list. I am not famous, but I feel this so deeply. I am truly sorry for the battles you face, be they external or internal, I am sorry that you have to face them. I hope you have someone close to lean on, if you don't, you can contact me, and I will listen. I've been down that road, I've towed that line. Sometimes, all you need is an ear.

Thank you for sharing this song with us. I hope it gets better for you man.
